        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2015_Solutions_2015s_page_005_15",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "for some r,s. If s = 0, then clearly all powers of M are in xS. Also, if r = 0, then one easily checks that M3 is in S.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5581451251003658,
          0.13808139535670502,
          0.9193042869239177,
          0.17881944425035634
        ],
        "order": 7
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2015_Solutions_2015s_page_005_16",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "We now assume rs # 0, and show that in that case M cannot be in S. First, note that the characteristic polynomial of M is 12 - 2rx - 85, and since M is nonsingular (as s # 0), this is also the minimal polynomial of M by the Cayley-Hamilton theorem. By repeatedly using the relation M2 = 2rM + 8571, we see that for each positive integer, we have Mk = IM + ukI for unique real constants Ik, Uk (uniqueness follows from the independence of M and I). Since M is in S, we see that M' lies in S only if uk = 0.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5545112848301682,
          0.18601190485313757,
          0.9194659882032625,
          0.3330592315411673
        ],
        "order": 8
      }
    ]
  },
