        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "We claim that these are also the only matrices in S satisfying the given condition. Indeed, suppose M = aA + BB where a B # 0. Let C = (- I/V2) with inverse C-' = (1/22 1//2) If we define D = C-'MC, then D = 2a (iT) where y = -Buz -. Now suppose that Mk is in S with k ≥ 2. Since (1-1) A (-1) = (1-1) B (4) = 0, we have (1 -1) Mk (-1) = 0, and so the upper left entry of CMC = Dk is 0. On the other hand, from the expression for D, an easy induction on k shows that Dk = (2a)* (Y PAK), where Pk is defined inductively by po = 0, p1 = 1, Pk+2 = 7 Pk + Pk+1. In particular, it follows from the inductive definition that pk > 0 when k≥ 1, whence the upper left entry of Dk is nonzero when k ≥ 2, a contradiction.",
        "bbox": [
